Exploring the Titanic Dataset

Reading the csv file

df <- read.csv("titanic_full.csv", stringsAsFactors = TRUE, na.strings = c("", "NA"))

Printing the names of the columns

names(df)
##  [1] "PassengerId" "Survived"    "Pclass"      "Name"        "Sex"        
##  [6] "Age"         "SibSp"       "Parch"       "Ticket"      "Fare"       
## [11] "Cabin"       "Embarked"    "WikiId"      "Name_wiki"   "Age_wiki"   
## [16] "Hometown"    "Boarded"     "Destination" "Lifeboat"    "Body"       
## [21] "Class"

Out of these columns, the categorical variables are: Survived, Pclass, Sex, Embarked, Boarded, and Class. Let’s explore each of them using the table function:

table(df$Survived, useNA = "ifany")
## 
##    0    1 <NA> 
##  549  342  418

It can be seen that there are 418 missing values in the “Survived” column

table(df$Pclass, useNA = "ifany")
## 
##   1   2   3 
## 323 277 709

It can be seen that there are 0 missing values in the “Pclass” column

table(df$Sex, useNA = "ifany")
## 
## female   male 
##    466    843

It can be seen that there are 0 missing values in the “Sex” column

table(df$Embarked, useNA = "ifany")
## 
##    C    Q    S <NA> 
##  270  123  914    2

It can be seen that there are 2 missing values in the “Embarked” column

table(df$Boarded, useNA = "ifany")
## 
##     Belfast   Cherbourg  Queenstown Southampton        <NA> 
##          10         259         119         916           5

It can be seen that there are 5 missing values in the “Boarded” column

table(df$Class, useNA = "ifany")
## 
##    1    2    3 <NA> 
##  326  272  706    5

It can be seen that there are 5 missing values in the “Class” column

Exploring Pairs of Categorical Variables Using xtabs() Function

xtabs(~Boarded+Embarked, data = df, addNA = TRUE)
##              Embarked
## Boarded         C   Q   S <NA>
##   Belfast       0   0  10    0
##   Cherbourg   242   0  17    0
##   Queenstown    0 118   1    0
##   Southampton  25   5 884    2
##   <NA>          3   0   2    0
xtabs(~Pclass+Class, data = df, addNA = TRUE)
##       Class
## Pclass   1   2   3 <NA>
##      1 321   0   0    2
##      2   5 272   0    0
##      3   0   0 706    3

The result above shows that there are no missing values in Pclass, so we can consider it in our final cleaned data.

xtabs(~Sex+Survived, data = df, addNA = TRUE)
##         Survived
## Sex        0   1 <NA>
##   female  81 233  152
##   male   468 109  266

This result shows prima facie that more males lost their lives. However, more analysis needs to be done for the missing values.

xtabs(~Pclass+Sex, data = df, addNA = TRUE)
##       Sex
## Pclass female male
##      1    144  179
##      2    106  171
##      3    216  493

The number of males is more than females in all the three classes.
